explanation:
Ideal voltmeter is connected between node a and b. Hence, replace it with its internal resistance R<sub>in</sub> = $$\infty $$, i.e., current through ideal voltmeter will be zero.
<br><br><img src="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1l9cvfoxv/2bf758f4-9a1e-418c-9cee-7d54188d4df6/e7916530-4e27-11ed-b459-6d2ae4022676/file-1l9cvfoxw.png?format=png" data-orsrc="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1l9cvfoxv/2bf758f4-9a1e-418c-9cee-7d54188d4df6/e7916530-4e27-11ed-b459-6d2ae4022676/file-1l9cvfoxw.png" loading="lazy" style="max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-height:40vh" alt="GATE ECE 2005 Network Theory - Two Port Networks Question 49 English Explanation">
<br><br>$$
\begin{aligned}
&amp;V_a=\frac{R_2}{R_1+R_2} \times 10=5 \mathrm{~V} \\\\
&amp;V_b=\frac{R_5}{R_3+R_5} \times 10=\frac{1.1}{2.1} \times 10=5.238 \mathrm{~V}
\end{aligned}
$$
<br><br>So, voltage across terminal $a b$ is
<br><br>$$
V_{a b}=V_a-V_b=-0.238 \mathrm{~V}
$$

